        <h1 property="schema:name">Conceptual Framework</h1><!-- for Linked Research -->
        <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">

<section>
  <h2>Effects of native Web technologies on scholarly communication</h2>
  <div>
    <p>In order to help us understand the effects of native Web technologies on scholarly communication, we can use <a href="http://dbpedia.org/Marshall_McLuhan" rel="cito:credits">Marshall McLuhan</a>'s tetrad on media effects as a heuristic device, a set of four questions, from the <cite><a href="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/981396559">Laws of Media</a></cite>:</p>

    <blockquote id="" rel="cito:includesQuotationFrom" cite="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/981396559">
      <ul>
        <li>What does it enhance or intensify?</li>
        <li>What does it render obsolete or displace?</li>
        <li>What does it retrieve that was previously obsolesced?</li>
        <li>What does it produce or become when pressed to an extreme?</li>
      </ul>
      <footer><cite><a href="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/981396559">Laws of Media</a></cite>, p. 7</footer>
    </blockquote>

    <p>The questions are presented in the appositional form, and correspond to the four effects: <q>enhances</q>, <q>obsolesces</q>, <q>retrieves</q>, and <q>reverses into</q>. We can use these terms to </p>

    <dl>
      <dt>Enhances</dt>
      <dd>access to information, decentralisation, response time, self-publishing, multi-modal content, social interactions, multi-dimensional information creation and consumption</dd>
      <dt>Obsolesces</dt>
      <dd>anti-sociality, print monopolies, distance, travel, centralised publishing, atomistic use of human senses, linear information creation and consumption</dd>
      <dt>Retrieves</dt>
      <dd>writing and correspondence, anarchy, direct representation</dd>
      <dt>Reverses into</dt>
      <dd>information overload, expensive precision and recall</dd>
    </dl>
  </div>
</section>

